WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:35.624 --> 00:40.624
Subtitles by explosiveskull

00:55.943 --> 00:58.679
We are never very far
from those we hate.

01:00.681 --> 01:02.982
For this very reason,

01:02.984 --> 01:06.220
we shall never be truly close
to those we love.

01:08.155 --> 01:11.123
An appalling fact.

01:11.125 --> 01:14.259
I knew it well enough
when I embarked.

01:14.261 --> 01:16.798
But some truths
deserve our attention.

01:18.298 --> 01:20.935
Others are best left alone.

01:23.637 --> 01:26.240
We set sail 67 days ago.

01:27.941 --> 01:30.979
September, 1914.

01:57.405 --> 02:02.711
Matches are useless as teats
on a bull above deck.

02:08.315 --> 02:09.717
Thank you.

02:13.988 --> 02:17.825
There's your island.
Look, you see it?

02:27.200 --> 02:29.103
What are you running from?

02:32.840 --> 02:34.873
That was the first question
they asked me

02:34.875 --> 02:36.678
when I decided to go to sea.

02:38.912 --> 02:41.915
Prepare to weigh anchor!

02:56.062 --> 02:59.731
That is a one man job.
Don't need two.

02:59.733 --> 03:01.033
Rusky, aren't you listening?

03:01.035 --> 03:02.834
Be careful with those
in the back!

03:02.836 --> 03:06.041
Don't get 'em wet!

03:07.775 --> 03:12.344
Careful with that.
Don't throw stuff about.

03:12.346 --> 03:18.053
Get that rope in! Rope!
Are you listening to me?

03:34.467 --> 03:37.903
Come on, come on!
Put him on the rope!

03:37.905 --> 03:39.374
Move it!

03:44.144 --> 03:45.810
No birds.

03:45.812 --> 03:49.116
No weather official
to greet you, either.

04:33.059 --> 04:35.326
Captain, sir,
where we leave the luggage

04:35.328 --> 04:36.929
of officer of air and winds?

04:36.931 --> 04:38.831
Here inside.

04:38.833 --> 04:41.499
Tell the others to hold off
with the rest of the provisions.

04:41.501 --> 04:43.235
No.
No, bring it forth.

04:43.237 --> 04:45.237
With respect,
I am responsible

04:45.239 --> 04:48.607
for your safe passage,
and this is hardly reassuring.

04:48.609 --> 04:50.945
And you've already provided
such passage.

05:06.059 --> 05:08.160
It had to be taken
as an act of kindness

05:08.162 --> 05:11.196
that the captain accompanied me
onto dry land.

05:11.198 --> 05:15.033
Nothing obliged him,
but during the journey,

05:15.035 --> 05:16.968
we had come to one of those
understandings

05:16.970 --> 05:20.240
that sometimes arise between
men of different generations.

05:21.975 --> 05:24.076
The captain
always treated me

05:24.078 --> 05:26.280
with the courtesy
of an executioner.

05:28.082 --> 05:32.153
If he could do anything
for me... he would.

05:43.097 --> 05:46.301
Boys?
Go back to the boat.

06:23.237 --> 06:26.241
You in there!
Open up!

06:34.547 --> 06:36.316
Can you hear me?!

06:40.688 --> 06:42.523
Hello!

07:16.523 --> 07:17.991
Hello?

07:41.515 --> 07:44.085
Hey! Wake up.

07:46.587 --> 07:49.720
Fetch water toad.

07:49.722 --> 07:53.759
Wake up!
Maritime signal technician.

07:53.761 --> 07:57.396
We are replacing the weather
official, Aldor Vigeland.

07:57.398 --> 07:59.366
Can you tell me
of his whereabouts?

08:06.073 --> 08:09.443
I said where is
the weather official?

08:13.047 --> 08:15.614
Listen here, I'm captain
of a ship in transit.

08:15.616 --> 08:18.115
I had to change course
to bring this man here

08:18.117 --> 08:20.785
and take his predecessor away.

08:20.787 --> 08:23.457
- Now where is...
- Typhus.

08:25.058 --> 08:28.593
- He's dead?
- Do you have any tobacco?

08:28.595 --> 08:30.261
Vodka?

08:30.263 --> 08:33.530
Where are the man's remains?

08:33.533 --> 08:36.037
Christ, man, speak up!

08:40.139 --> 08:42.808
He went out one day.
I never saw him again.

08:42.809 --> 08:47.212
For God's sake, it's an island!
How far could he have gone?

08:47.214 --> 08:48.447
A swim?

08:48.449 --> 08:50.685
Your name?

08:54.088 --> 08:55.687
Gruner.

08:55.689 --> 08:57.823
You like Frazer?

08:57.825 --> 09:00.294
That's not my book.

09:01.295 --> 09:03.495
You, you have tobacco?

09:03.497 --> 09:05.366
Not on my person, no.

09:06.767 --> 09:08.632
Ah.

09:10.104 --> 09:12.706
Mr. Gruner.

09:28.888 --> 09:30.390
Captain.

09:31.725 --> 09:33.391
I appreciate your concern,

09:33.393 --> 09:35.430
but I'm not about
to turn back now.

09:37.697 --> 09:38.832
Take this.

09:40.533 --> 09:43.568
Don't mistake stubbornness
with stupidity.

09:43.570 --> 09:47.407
I'll manage.
Thank you for all you've done.

09:50.576 --> 09:53.844
Eat well.
Work hard.

09:53.846 --> 09:55.449
Stay busy.

09:59.452 --> 10:00.519
Fair winds.

10:00.521 --> 10:03.524
And following seas.

10:21.675 --> 10:25.676
I would have to live
in a solitude-like exile

10:25.678 --> 10:29.514
for 12 months
far from civilization

10:29.516 --> 10:32.383
with a job as monotonous
as it was insignificant...

10:32.385 --> 10:35.322
to log the intensity
and direction of the winds.

15:13.499 --> 15:15.666
Mr. Gruner?

15:22.075 --> 15:23.710
Mr. Gruner?

15:25.644 --> 15:26.877
Mr. Gruner, if this is your idea
of an initi...

18:20.352 --> 18:22.121
Open the door!

18:26.892 --> 18:28.294
Let me in!

18:33.933 --> 18:35.135
Gruner?!

18:37.036 --> 18:38.705
Gruner!

18:42.876 --> 18:44.311
Gruner!

18:50.750 --> 18:52.282
Please let me in!

18:52.284 --> 18:53.987
Should've stayed on the boat

18:55.921 --> 18:57.357
Gruner!

19:06.232 --> 19:07.801
Gruner!

19:17.476 --> 19:20.278
When I have fears
that I may cease to be,

19:20.280 --> 19:24.115
before my pen has gleaned
my teeming brain,

19:24.117 --> 19:26.951
before high-piled books,
in charactery

19:26.953 --> 19:30.120
hold like rich garners
the full ripened grain,

19:30.122 --> 19:33.124
when I behold
upon the night's starred face

19:33.126 --> 19:36.359
huge cloudy symbols
of a high romance

19:36.361 --> 19:39.163
and think that I may never
live to trace their shadows

19:39.165 --> 19:41.765
with the magic hand of chance,

19:41.767 --> 19:44.969
and when I feel,
fair creature of an hour,

19:44.971 --> 19:47.070
that I shall never look
upon thee more,

19:47.072 --> 19:49.307
Never have relish
in the faery power

19:49.309 --> 19:51.242
of unreflecting love,

19:51.244 --> 19:55.512
then on the shore of
the wide world I stand alone,

19:55.514 --> 19:59.786
and think till love and fame
to nothingness do sink.

20:55.007 --> 20:56.476
Mother of God.

26:11.623 --> 26:13.890
No! Don't shoot!

26:13.892 --> 26:15.494
Put your gun down!

26:19.365 --> 26:20.534
Put it down!

26:29.675 --> 26:30.844
Step back.

26:32.611 --> 26:34.246
Step back!

26:37.582 --> 26:38.715
What do you want?

26:38.717 --> 26:40.753
Do I really need
to spell it out?

26:44.423 --> 26:45.923
You said you have tobacco?

26:45.925 --> 26:47.892
Yes.

26:47.894 --> 26:50.627
- Coffee?
- Yes.

26:50.629 --> 26:54.798
- Vodka?
- Gin. And ammunition.

26:54.800 --> 26:56.503
Caliber?

27:04.243 --> 27:05.712
There's plenty more.

27:08.747 --> 27:11.848
- She's harmless.
- Harmless?

27:11.850 --> 27:14.186
Come here.
Come here,

27:16.688 --> 27:18.257
Come on.

27:19.926 --> 27:22.492
Good girl, easy.
Good.

27:22.494 --> 27:24.531
See?

27:27.600 --> 27:30.704
I think I'll call you...
Friend.

27:48.788 --> 27:50.421
You got bit?

27:50.423 --> 27:51.558
Burned.

27:53.225 --> 27:55.695
- How many'd you kill?
- Don't know.

27:58.397 --> 28:01.999
The previous weather official.
It wasn't typhus.

28:02.001 --> 28:05.501
You left him stranded here
like me.

28:05.503 --> 28:07.771
It's as good as murder.

28:07.773 --> 28:09.576
We gotta go.

28:21.419 --> 28:22.688
Come on!

28:53.019 --> 28:54.554
Pain gone?

28:56.656 --> 28:59.792
- How long was I out for?
- Day or two by my reckoning.

29:01.494 --> 29:02.829
Pissed your pants.

29:17.076 --> 29:19.643
1,862.

29:19.645 --> 29:22.482
Now that's what I call
an armory.

29:25.083 --> 29:26.916
What's it doing?

29:26.918 --> 29:30.724
Stupid thing.
Thinks stuff'll float away.

29:33.458 --> 29:35.425
You can speak with the beasts.

29:35.427 --> 29:36.963
Not speak, command.

29:39.831 --> 29:41.498
Doesn't it try and escape?

29:41.500 --> 29:44.335
Does a dog leave even
the cruelest of masters?

29:44.337 --> 29:47.538
It's incredible.

29:47.540 --> 29:50.574
I never even imagined
such things could exist.

29:50.576 --> 29:52.443
What we know is a small island

29:52.445 --> 29:54.513
in the vast ocean
of what we don't.

30:00.086 --> 30:02.051
I've heard that there
are atolls that contain

30:02.053 --> 30:03.953
unique and endemic species
of fish

30:03.955 --> 30:06.089
that have evolved
completely independently.

30:07.859 --> 30:11.028
Hangover species that have
survived in isolation,

30:11.030 --> 30:14.000
stuck in a kind
of evolutionary stalemate.

30:16.702 --> 30:18.402
Maybe these beasts
are like that,

30:18.404 --> 30:23.810
not quite human nor amphibian,
reptile or fish.

30:25.144 --> 30:27.881
She's not quite like
the others, is she?

30:30.049 --> 30:32.715
This one doesn't bite,
that's all.

30:32.717 --> 30:35.452
What about that scar
on your shoulder?

30:35.454 --> 30:37.087
There was one time.

30:37.089 --> 30:39.525
The only time.
She learned her lesson.

30:41.860 --> 30:44.994
Remember, it's the still
and silent sea

30:44.996 --> 30:46.699
that drowns a man.

30:53.638 --> 30:56.973
I adjusted the mechanism
to sweep the coastline.

30:56.975 --> 31:00.877
All I know is that the toads,
like all infernal beasts,

31:00.879 --> 31:04.114
they shun light,
human or divine.

31:04.116 --> 31:06.416
Demons from Atlantis.

31:06.418 --> 31:08.786
I believe in what I see.

31:08.788 --> 31:11.155
One thing I still can't
understand

31:11.157 --> 31:13.690
is that you could have escaped
four days ago on the boat

31:13.692 --> 31:16.126
- that brought me here.
- Escape? To where?

31:16.128 --> 31:17.860
To a civilized world.

31:17.862 --> 31:22.065
Nice place,
that civilized world of yours.

31:22.067 --> 31:23.770
That why you gave it up?

31:25.670 --> 31:28.105
Here I'm master
of my own destiny,

31:28.107 --> 31:30.174
- come hell or high water.
- Well, you can keep it.

31:30.176 --> 31:32.909
I'm signaling the first ship
that passes by.

31:32.911 --> 31:36.646
Really? This island is not on
any commercial shipping lanes.

31:36.648 --> 31:38.182
The next ship here will be
the one with your replacement.

31:38.184 --> 31:40.017
Come on, Gruner,
lighthouses are built

31:40.019 --> 31:41.684
- where there's naval transit.
- They're also built

31:41.686 --> 31:44.221
to balance navy budgets
and siphon funds.

31:44.223 --> 31:48.427
Gotta empty a bucket before
you can fill it up again, boy.

31:53.498 --> 31:57.436
It is the second time in a
week I'm forced to rebuild my life.

31:59.003 --> 32:02.572
All my belongings are burned.

32:02.574 --> 32:04.910
I've nothing from the person
I used to be.

32:06.145 --> 32:08.578
In this remote part
of the world,

32:08.580 --> 32:11.048
I feel a sense
of irreparable loss.

32:11.050 --> 32:15.918
I can't tell whether it arises
from a longing for civilization,

32:15.920 --> 32:19.255
a prisoner's panic...

32:19.257 --> 32:20.759
or simply fear.

33:12.645 --> 33:14.912
Don't!
Don't eat that.

33:14.914 --> 33:17.517
It's... it's not edi...

33:20.084 --> 33:21.854
It's a can...

33:24.255 --> 33:26.525
Friend, get your rifle.

33:58.089 --> 33:59.956
Don't shoot till
they reach the tower,

33:59.958 --> 34:01.925
and don't waste bullets
on their wounded.

34:01.927 --> 34:04.230
Give them enough carrion,
they'll devour each other.

34:26.085 --> 34:28.117
I don't see anything.

34:28.119 --> 34:30.353
You'll learn
what to look for.

34:58.884 --> 35:00.217
Come on!

35:00.219 --> 35:03.085
Come on!

35:03.087 --> 35:05.154
Shoot, man! Use your gun!

35:12.264 --> 35:13.900
Come on, shoot!

36:18.297 --> 36:20.797
No man is an island.

36:20.799 --> 36:26.869
Horse shit.
Gruner is an island.

36:26.871 --> 36:30.507
Gruner does not need
any dead weight,

36:30.509 --> 36:36.148
no matter how much chocolate
and coffee ladybird brought!

36:41.319 --> 36:44.256
Go fetch some water.

38:11.944 --> 38:13.311
One last chance.

39:13.205 --> 39:16.375
Hold. Hold fast.

39:18.342 --> 39:21.578
Wait. Hold.

39:23.147 --> 39:24.382
Steady.

39:31.156 --> 39:34.590
Behind you!
Wake up, man! Wake up!

39:34.592 --> 39:39.462
Shoot! Shoot, dammit! Shoot!
Shoot! One last chance!

39:52.210 --> 39:55.378
Gruner,
wait, don't! Gruner!

39:57.214 --> 39:59.616
Gruner! Help!

39:59.618 --> 40:03.520
Gruner!
Gruner, let me in!

40:03.522 --> 40:06.188
Gruner!

41:45.523 --> 41:47.424
Gruner and I settled into

41:47.426 --> 41:52.462
a curious sort of co-existence
based on routine.

41:52.464 --> 41:55.398
The monsters always swarm
at night,

41:55.400 --> 41:59.201
their strikes growing longer
every day.

41:59.203 --> 42:01.570
The Japanese
philosopher Musashi said

42:01.572 --> 42:05.407
that only a few
appreciate the art of war.

42:05.409 --> 42:08.677
A good warrior is not defined by
the cause he defends

42:08.679 --> 42:11.449
but rather by the meaning
that derives from the struggle.

42:13.384 --> 42:15.784
Days are always the same.

42:15.786 --> 42:17.719
I abandon my post
on the balcony

42:17.721 --> 42:19.355
at the break of dawn.

42:19.357 --> 42:22.625
Nature dictates
the length of my slumber.

42:22.627 --> 42:25.427
I have to accept the most
ungrateful tasks

42:25.429 --> 42:28.299
simply to keep my place
inside the lighthouse.

42:29.868 --> 42:31.800
I've been meditating
on my reason

42:31.802 --> 42:33.205
for coming to this island.

42:36.208 --> 42:38.677
I had been seeking peace
through nothingness.

42:39.777 --> 42:42.277
But in place of silence,

42:42.279 --> 42:44.749
I found a monster-plagued
inferno.

42:48.853 --> 42:50.686
Smells strange.

42:50.688 --> 42:52.654
How do you know that
the herbs aren't bad?

42:52.656 --> 42:55.491
Herbs are like people.
They are neither good or bad.

42:55.493 --> 42:57.460
They're just known or unknown,
that's all.

42:57.462 --> 43:00.230
Herbs won't slit
your throat for money.

43:00.232 --> 43:02.831
A farmer keeps cows.
He cares for them.

43:02.833 --> 43:07.302
He feeds them.
He gives them endearing names.

43:07.304 --> 43:08.640
Like Daisy.

43:11.208 --> 43:13.311
But then he steals her milk.

43:15.212 --> 43:16.846
And he kills her children.

43:16.848 --> 43:18.882
Another riddle.

43:18.884 --> 43:20.849
It's a question
of necessity.

43:20.851 --> 43:23.219
Has it ever occurred to you
that it might be her wailing

43:23.221 --> 43:24.623
that attracts the beasts?

43:27.359 --> 43:30.192
But then why would they attack
some nights and not others?

43:30.194 --> 43:33.163
And why would she lure her
own kin to die on the rocks?

43:33.165 --> 43:35.297
The only thing you need
to understand

43:35.299 --> 43:39.268
is that we are the invaders,
which makes us the enemy.

43:39.270 --> 43:42.838
Kill and conquer,
that's what we humans do.

43:42.840 --> 43:45.507
You want to conquer them.
Is that it?

43:45.509 --> 43:47.879
Oh, no,
I want to exterminate them.

43:58.223 --> 43:59.558
We need more timber.

44:02.226 --> 44:03.793
Why?

44:03.795 --> 44:05.865
We haven't been attacked
in weeks.

44:07.866 --> 44:09.902
You like sleeping
in my lighthouse.

44:19.511 --> 44:21.413
Faded.

44:22.647 --> 44:24.183
Far away.

44:26.650 --> 44:28.353
Dissolved.

44:34.292 --> 44:35.627
And quite forgotten.

44:56.248 --> 45:00.817
My eyes have scrutinized
every surface a thousand times.

45:00.819 --> 45:03.353
We speak of the lighthouse
and its environs

45:03.355 --> 45:06.021
as if it were an entire state.

45:06.023 --> 45:08.194
Every nook
and cranny has a name.

45:09.493 --> 45:11.460
Every rock.

45:11.462 --> 45:12.931
Every stone.

45:19.036 --> 45:21.839
Maybe they migrate,
like the whales in winter.

45:24.808 --> 45:27.409
Or maybe the creatures reason
they can't defeat us.

45:27.411 --> 45:29.411
They're beasts.

45:29.413 --> 45:33.516
They are out there gathering in
numbers for their next attack.

45:33.518 --> 45:35.487
You're on watch.

45:42.993 --> 45:45.395
Although it may seem strange,

45:45.397 --> 45:47.529
the lulls between fighting
are often worse

45:47.531 --> 45:49.400
than the battles themselves.

45:51.435 --> 45:52.735
This void is accompanied

45:52.737 --> 45:55.340
by the mascot's change
in attitude.

46:30.875 --> 46:33.342
How could Gruner lie with one of
the very same monsters

46:33.344 --> 46:35.513
that plague us every night?

46:40.784 --> 46:45.520
How did he manage
to justify the act in defiance

46:45.522 --> 46:48.459
of all the obstacles
set down by civilization?

46:50.728 --> 46:52.297
Set down by nature.

47:08.480 --> 47:11.447
How could he get closer...

47:11.449 --> 47:12.885
and closer...

47:17.121 --> 47:20.525
and not be repelled
by her cold skin?

47:25.929 --> 47:27.765
I have decided
to give her a name.

47:29.534 --> 47:30.903
Aneris.

47:35.639 --> 47:37.442
Down.

48:00.998 --> 48:02.898
When'd we run out of potatoes?

48:02.900 --> 48:04.936
We didn't.
You're drinking 'em.

48:15.513 --> 48:16.848
You play?

48:17.848 --> 48:19.751
What civilized man doesn't?

48:24.788 --> 48:27.190
These beasts really are
a fascinating species.

48:27.192 --> 48:29.192
Take the blood,
for example.

48:29.194 --> 48:32.228
I imagine that it must
share the properties

48:32.230 --> 48:36.098
of some arctic fish containing
a kind of anti-freeze

48:36.100 --> 48:38.934
to help them to survive
in sub-zero conditions.

48:38.936 --> 48:42.070
Have you noticed that they've
got two sets of eyelids?

48:42.072 --> 48:43.773
Now the first,
very much like ours,

48:43.775 --> 48:46.576
but the second
is a transparent membrane

48:46.578 --> 48:48.511
helping them when they dive,
I would imagine.

48:48.513 --> 48:51.713
We could capture specimens,
take them back to Great Britain

48:51.715 --> 48:54.183
or to the United States,
present our discovery,

48:54.185 --> 48:56.585
- and we would be celebrated...
- All right, you got me!

48:56.587 --> 48:59.721
I came down to the asshole
of the world to become famous.

48:59.723 --> 49:01.724
All right? Check!

49:01.726 --> 49:03.494
Now shut up and play.

49:07.965 --> 49:09.201
Check mate.

49:14.505 --> 49:17.572
No, i-it can't be.

49:17.574 --> 49:19.074
I-it j...
it just can't be.

49:19.076 --> 49:21.043
Calm down, Gruner,
it's only a game.

49:21.045 --> 49:23.182
- Kings, pawns.
- It can't be!

49:25.817 --> 49:27.683
We forgot the light!

49:27.685 --> 49:29.221
Galley deck!

50:48.132 --> 50:51.537
I'm out! There's too many!
There's too many!

51:55.866 --> 51:57.668
So what do we know do now?

52:05.043 --> 52:08.213
♪ One starry night ♪

52:09.813 --> 52:14.150
♪ As I lay sleeping ♪

52:14.152 --> 52:17.987
♪ One starry night ♪

52:17.989 --> 52:20.989
♪ As I lay in bed ♪

52:22.125 --> 52:25.695
♪ I dreamed I heard ♪

52:25.697 --> 52:30.299
♪ Wagon wheels creakin' ♪

52:30.301 --> 52:36.842
